ological and political perspective, the authors challenge the traditional boundaries within the issue of the construction of Europe. In the first part, historians and anthropologists from various national traditions discuss the process of the construction of Europe and its implications for cultural identities. The second section examines a number of topics at the core of the process of Europeanization and presents up-to-date information on each of these issues: political parties, regions, football, cities, the Euro, ethnicity, heritage and European cinema. Emphasis is be placed on the political structuring of cultural identities by contrasting top-down and bottom-up processes that define the tensions between the unity and diversity of the European Community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aGroup identityvCross-cultural studies. 0aGroup identityzEuropean Union countries. 0aNationalismvCross-cultural studies. 0aNationalismzEuropean Union countries. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBromberger, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemossier, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemossier, Marion, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEverett, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrillo, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanley, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKockel, Ullrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilner, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThiesse, Anne-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVinen, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/